My Raise3d N2 has been very good to me, but it needs a little rise in the lid design to clear the bend in the filament tubes as they enter the extruder. I use mostly PLA, but where the N2 sits is near an AC duct and the N2 needs the lid.

Downside could be in certain cases one would have to watch the bed temperature

Thanks a lot for all the predecessors.
I tried all of those ducts with more or less success.
The one I remixed mine from seemed to be the most promising with the recess for the PINDA and space for the silicone sock and all...
I have no clue how all the others printers and their parts did look, but mine would not
want to fit wit my extruder, especially with the thin wall between fan and extruder lid.
I just did remove the latter and made some room for the fan.
After doing some test prints with the usual Marvins, Benchys and Treefrogs for me
it is a great improvement to the original Prusa-Nozzle of my I3 MK2S KIT. (which as such is not that bad at all...)

Made with PETG from these guys https://www.3dpsp.de/ as all my other printer parts.
No drooping or degrading at all....
This stuff turned out to be quite fine to process.
It is quite sturdy, no problems with adhesion at all.
And really nice and brilliant colours for a reasonable price.

You can build basic structures with the core ZoD sets, though now that we're getting more comfortable with the building parameters we're ready to start branching out to include full building accessories. This kit has everything you need to make a basic house, and you can swap parts out with other ZoD tile themes or use these components in your dungeon builds.

We designed these 3d-printable files to be optimized for home printing and cover a wide (and expanding) variety of themes and genres. Whether you use them for RPG dungeon-delves, wargaming scenics, or anything else, these tiles print and assemble fast and easy and come off your build plate ready to paint!

-Z.O.D. tiles are optimized to print along the Z axis, meaning you can get high definition on details, use less material (0% infill), and fit more tiles per print.
Because of the vertical printing, each floor tile is reversible, printing with two floor textures each.

-Z.O.D. tiles print easily in one piece and never require support material.

-Tiles easily slide or snap together for a firm hold, ensuring that each piece you print is textured to be part of the map.

-Each tile segment prints in an average of 45 minutes, and you can print one at a time to avoid curling if that's an issue for your machine.

-All genre themes will interlock, allowing you to mix and match from any set.
Z.O.D. tiles are designed for use with 28mm/Heroic scale miniatures, though we will offer options for 15mm and 6mm scale gaming as well.

-Wall tiles use their own channels and do not infringe on the floor grids, each of which perfectly accommodates a 25mm/1" base.

-Try printing your Z.O.D. tiles in black filament (ABS or PLA) and skip the priming phase, painting directly onto the surface!

For those of you who follow us on Patreon (or if you're considering doing so), our patrons will receive every design file we make for this series. Just be sure and set your monthly cap at something you're comfortable paying (because we tend to be fairly prolific).

Because these pieces rely on certain print settings, you'll want to observe the following print guidelines;

-Try printing one tile at a time first.

-Print at 0% infill for the best results.

-You don't need support, but a raft may be helpful (depending on your printer and material).

-We print ours at a .2 layer height, though you could try for higher resolution if you prefer.

-When printing Spacers, you may want to print them so the connector channels print along the X axis (side to side), though this may depend on your printer. Also, arranging them tightly in groups (as the spacers are presented here) will help keep them from warping.

-We've had equally good results in both ABS and PLA.

Enjoy!

-A special note to our Patreon supporters- All of our patrons will get the full compliment of Z.O.D. sets as they're released, regardless of whether or not they back the Kickstarter campaign.

description.text:
Disclaimer: This model may not be the best choice for a beginner.

Update 12/22/17 I added a version with rounded corners. I haven't printed it, so let me know if it works and I'll do the other one. There are a couple layers that bridge the pick opening, but with care you should be able to insert the pick into the cavity.

This handle is designed to encapsulate lock picks that have handles and are 8 x 1.8 x 80 mm. These handles are generally furnished with the lock pick kits with the clear plastic practice lock found on Banggood, Aliexpress, and other sites.

The way I use this model is that you stop the print at the layer just before the lock pick cavity top surface is printed and insert the lock pick with handle. When you restart the printer, the top layers are printed and the pick is embedded in the handle. Make sure the side with the holes is against the print bed. Also, it is a good idea to check the interior of the cavity with a file before inserting the handle so you can remove any bits of filament that might prevent the handle from laying flat in the cavity.

There are two designs: one for a pick that exits the center of the handle and one that accommodates a pick up to handle width, so picks that exit either the left or right side of the handle can be used.

You could print the handle in two pieces and then glue them together. Also, you could remove the two handle pieces and use one of the other pick handle designs on Thingiverse and insert only the pick layer into the handle.

IMPORTANT: When inserting the assembled pick into the print, make sure that the side of the handle with the head of the rivets is placed against the print bed so that the rivet heads fit into the holes in the bottom. If the flattened side of the rivets protrude too high, either press them down or file some of it off so it is only a few thousandths high, otherwise the print head may hit it. A slight bump by the print head is generally OK.

I'll list the techniques I use to pause the printer; your printer may or may not work with these.

  1. If your printer firmware supports the the M600 command, you can patch that into the G-Code at the beginning of the layer that prints over the open cavity. This command moves the print head to a park position and waits for you to push a button on the printer to resume.
  2. You can patch the G-Code to manually move the print head and pause the printer. Insert the following as above:
    G1 X150 - this moves the print head to X=150 mm
    @pause - this command is for Repetier Host and probably only Repetier Host

I used 2 perimeters, 2 or 3 bottom layers and 3 top layers. Make sure you check the depth of the cavity and adjust Z scale factor if the cavity isn't deep enough. I printed with the cavity height of 7-8 layers @ 0.3 mm.
File off the edges of the handle to make it more comfortable to hold.

description.text:
Designed these more so for fashion over function. Despite that, I've noticed much less vibration at my top spool (with the additional help of https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2573749), which used to wobble violently during prints.

I don't have a lot of experience with supported prints, so my V1 (purple) didn't turn out perfect, but it still fits snugly into position and stays put. I've since uploaded V2 (green), which has printed-in supports (to be cut out after completion), deeper channel for the vertical acrylic piece, more features for brace functionality, better looking. I left V1 up for reference of progress. Print as shown.

Channel width in the model file is 8 mm, which was based on the provided specifications. My caliper gauge measured 7.8 mm, but my V2 print fits super good and tight. If for some reason your prints fit too loosely to withstand the vibrations of printing, discontinue use or they may fall off during a print and cause various problems.

Printer Brand:

Prusa

Printer:

Prusa Clone

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.2

Infill:

25%

V2: I used 15% infill and printed at 50 mm/s. Started at 199 C for good bed-bond, then after a few layers turned down to 196 C and fan up to 50%. Increased fan to 100% just before overhanging layers, then back down to 50% after and in between. Some drooping in those overhanging layers, but actually proved favorable in the horizontal channel by making a tighter fit. No further modification after cutting out printed-in supports. One attempt, one success.

V1: I used 17% infill which produced the mesh pattern shown, but apparently wasn't enough infill for the top layers to bond in some places and get 100% coverage.

description.text:
This is a work in progress. I still have many tweaks to be made and is not ready for primetime.
I'm posting it to get input and seed some ideas.

So basically it's designed to run spring loaded on the Z axis of a milling machine and use a limit switch to signal the cam software that the milling bit is in contact with the copper clad board. I just redesigned the locking collar, since the first one was too tight. I have not printed it yet, but it's a portion of the vacuum collar, so should be good. I got the v-slide close, but I need to close up the gap a little and fix the limit switch mounting.
The threaded tube is used to adjust the cutting depth and track the surface of the copper clad board. If you ever want consistent cutting depth you have to either map the whole board and add offsets to your z-axis g-code numbers OR follow the contour. You can get away with course z-axis settings if you can get away with greater then say 16mil traces, but if you want 8-10mil traces you've got to track the surface. The larger the PCB you're attempting the larger the error without tracking or mapping. I added a vacuum port, since there is no escaping the depth collar for millings. I may add intake slots on the depth collar to get better air flow.

I used this motor and collet first:

http://www.ebay.com/itm/Mini-Hand-Drill-DIY-Lathe-Press-555-Motor-w-1-8-Chuck-Mounting-Bracket-12-24V/361989772460?ssPageName=STRK%3AMEBIDX%3AIT&_trksid=p2060353.m2749.l2649

But I want to try this one:

http://www.ebay.com/itm/1-5-3-17mm-Collet-Electric-DC12V-Motor-Drill-with-24-Twist-Drill-Bits-Wrenches-/391804304064?hash=item5b395b3ac0:g:UIYAAOSwKytZMsXk

next, so I can shrink the depth gauge collar to track less surface, yielding a smaller averaged area.

It's still an unknown regarding run-out which is my next worry for cutting wobble.

More work to be done!

title: Humanoid Robot - Work In Progress Updated 11-8-17

description.text:
This is a model I originally started designing with Shapr3D on my iPad Pro. However, I decided that I wanted to do some things that Shapr3D is not ready for yet.

This has been 100% redesigned using Autodesk Fusion 360. No parts have been reused from the Shapr3D model.

NOTE: The STL files have now been uploaded for the right and left legs. More files to come soon. Keep in mind these may change as the model gets closer to completion. I am printing the updated parts now and will have images once printed and assembled.

I have test printed and fitted most of the parts already. I plan on making this so that you can use all of the Trossen Robotics HR-OS1 electronics and hopefully you can use the software as well at least as a starting point to creating your own. The HR-OS1 project is Open Source best I can tell, however all parts have been redesigned to be 3D printable as well as slightly larger to give the robot an even greater appearance.

This will likely change many times as I go on. Once I do that I am hoping to model a fully enclosed body and head.

As stated this is work in progress. Much like the RC Helicopter Model (still working on it) is. Also see the hexabot that was modeled to resemble the Phanton X by Trossen Robotics.

This is fully designed with Autodesk Fusion 360

This has been mostly designed on a Custom Built PC running an Intel Core i9-7900X CPU, EVGA GeForce 1080Ti SC2 Hybrid with 64GB RAM and the 1TB Samsung 960 Pro NVME M.2 SSD running Windows 10 Pro.

This PC was built specifically for Autodesk Fusion 360 as I burned up an ASUS Laptop and a Mac Mini running Fusion 360 when rendering this project and attempting some basic animation.

I am very new to Autodesk Fusion 360 as I have spent the last 8+ months learning on Shapr3D as I never could understand desktop CAD software. All credit for my modeling experience goes to Shapr3D. Now I spend countless hours learning Autodesk Fusion 360 and watching as many tutorial videos as I can.

Please let me know what you think of the model (images of it anyway) and please check out my other work. The hexabot will also have more work completed at some point and I plan on finishing the RC Helicopter model as well, however that is not meant to actually fly, it is just for the experience of modeling it.

description.text:
This is an enhanced and customizable version of the sieve by pcstru.
Enter Customizer to create a model with your own desired specifications.

This updated version allows to choose between round or square shapes, or you can make any regular polygon shape by reducing the number of circle segments. The polygon will fit inside a circle of the specified outer diameter (this means making a 4-sided polygon is not the same as selecting the ‘square’ shape).
Another tweak creates the model such that the grid should be well-attached to the rim even when using few or thin strands, and my unstoppable urge for detail made me ensure that the grid is perfectly centered at all times.

You can opt to print the grid as one set of layers, i.e. a plane with holes in it, or to print two sets of strands on top of each other (‘offset’ option). The latter is easier and probably faster to print, and may yield a more accurate filter if hole size is important. The disadvantage is that dirt tends to stick to the filter more easily.

You can also opt to lift the grid. This allows to print accurate filters with strands only as thick as your nozzle diameter (see photos). Set the lift distance to your first layer height to ensure the filter only starts being printed at the second layer. This avoids that the strands get squished against the bed, or printed with a wider first layer extrusion, both of which would make the hole size inaccurate. You could also use a raft to the same effect, but it might be difficult to remove the filter form the raft without damaging it.

title: FPV Racer Simulation Goggle Adapter Mount

description.text:
This is more about how to connect your goggles to an FPV simulator than the mount but the mount is part of making it all work together nicely. (It prints without support if you orientate it onto it's back.)

If your goggles require composite (RCA) video input then running an FPV simulator in your goggles will require an adapter in cases where your video card only supports HDMI out. This mount will allow an HDMI2RCA (composite) video adapter to mount on the goggle strap in close enough proximity to use the 3.5mm mini plug to RCA adapter included with Quanum DYI FPV V2 goggles.

In order to convert the signal I found 2 viable options:

A. Purchase an inexpensive adapter and connect it directly between your HDMI output or HDMI split output of your PC. (Note: this will operate with no additional power supplied to the adapter).

https://www.amazon.com/Converter-Adapter-Charger-USCMHColumbus-inventory/dp/B01M749T42/ref=sr_1_3?ie=UTF8&qid=1507666601&sr=8-3&keywords=hdmi2av

B. If you have a Raspberry PI connect the goggles to the composite video output of the PI. Install Moonlight Embedded on your PI. Set up composite video support in config.txt . Write a startup script to launch Moonlight which connects to your PC that supports Gamestream or Steamlink. Pair your PI to your PC. If you are using Quanum V2's ensure you launch moonlight executable in the appropriate resolution. i.e. "moonlight stream -width 800 -height 480 -unsupported [host ip] . It is necessary to include the "-unsupported" option to get it to run in the specified resolution. In the case of Quanum V2's the 5" TFT screen resolution is 800x480.

More on Moonlight usage here:

https://github.com/irtimmer/moonlight-embedded/wiki/Usage

The second option is viable and potentially can give you a wireless stream to the goggles but the PI still requires power and remains a bit cumbersome to set up and operate. My recommendation from running both is to spend the few bucks on the HDMI2AV converter and suffer with the cable by supporting it with the odd strategically placed Velcro strap.

A free fully functional FPV simulator is available here from DRL to try out and see if you want to invest in anything more.

https://thedroneracingleague.com/videogame/download/

description.text: Hello Thingiverse! I was tinkering around and decided that I wanted to make a keychain. Notes:

The most important thing to know when printing this is that it need to print long ways with the joints facing up(as seen in the stl). It should import into a slicer like this, but I just want to be sure everyone is able to print it. After some testing I found that printing at 115% works the best for the monoprice maker select mini, as it cannot do the joints well at smaller sizes. I think most other printers can handle it at 100% or smaller. As far a destiny goes I would say 30%-50% to keep it strong and durable. Adhesion wise I would recommend a brim so the each link hold on the print surface. For speed I wouldn't think it would make a big difference in functionality, but for time and quality 50 mms should be the best. Also supports are NOT needed to print.

After your print is finished peel off the keychain, and any supports/bed adhesion. Slowly and gently apply pressure to each of the links until it snaps and can move. The keychain will be very rigid at first, but with more use it will break in. Simply put it on you key ring and you're good to go!

Menger sponges (or cubes, whatever) are interesting objects. 
The really interesting question is what the cross section looks like if you cut it in half. 
No! not like that! Cut it in half perpendicular to a body diagonal!
Now try to imagine the outline and the inside outlines..... 
Anyway. Menger cubes get complicated really, really quickly. Apparently openscad can handle a level two just fine, but level 3 is beyond the capacity of my computer. Oh well.

Compile the C program. (I used: gcc -Wall -O2 menger.c -o menger ) Run
menger 0 > m0.scad
menger 1 > m1.scad
menger 2 > m2.scad
menger 3 > m3.scad Now you have the scad files for four levels of menger sponges.
The attached "hm2.scad" creates HALF a menger cube. Cut, you guessed it, perpendicular to a body diagonal. This prints best on my ultimaker with two layers of outside wall and NO infill. The infill causes a wire-mess that is difficult to clean up. Print two copies, fit them together and put them on the coffee table. When one of your guests notices it, ask them to predict the pattern on the slicing plane.... When adding I found a menger sponge already on thingiverse.

comments.text:
I really liked the look of this part, so I printed the small version first, with the intention to print a 70% scaled version of the larger one next.
My printer is well controlled, with little backlash etc, but the joint gaps at the small scale result an a lot of fusing. Having said that, 30 minutes with a small scalpel loosened the legs and head joints. I am pleased to say that the leg joints pivot well on their axles, but I was disappointed to discover, using netfabb, that the pivot point for the head is not in the middle of the radius, so it will never move by more than the small gap will allow. It's a 9/10 generally, with 2/10 for the head.

description.text:
I wanted to install a smart thermostat in my house to save on heating. But I rent and the heating system is line voltage, so replacing the thermostat and messing with the electric system was not the best idea. So what better excuse to to do some 3D printing and automate the thermostat that's already there?

This model is a duplicate of the cover for the thermostat, but with mounts for a servo. Also included is an adapter that connects the servo to the thermostat axle. The servo can then be connected to an ESP8266 and be remotely controlled from the internet.

I used an SG92R servo, a NodeMCU ESP8266 board and a DHT22 for telemetry.

This is a Lin Black Bulky Bobbin for spinning wheels in an easily printable, modular format.

The front end is a single piece and has a small insert for the bobbin core. The insert is slightly larger than the core, but even so it can be tricky to get in the first time.
The back end is in three pieces: the main part, whorl1 and whorl2. There is a small recess in whorl2 so that the two pieces fit well together. Both whorl pieces fit onto the "nose" of the back end -- the order doesn't matter.

I printed on an Anet A8 with 0.4mm nozzle at 0.2mm/layer and 15% infill.

I found that the pieces fit together snugly enough that glue was not needed. But I will probably glue the core and the main end pieces just to be safe.

description.text:
I was approached by a parent whose son had undergone surgery for bone cancer in his leg. Due to the titanium implant in his leg, one leg grows faster than the other. After complaining that the wedge prescribed to him by the physical therapist was too short and didn't allow his foot to stay level, the parent requested for me to redesign the wooden block to be a centimeter taller.

After scanning, measuring, and redesigning in Fusion360, I raised the height of the wedge by a centimeter while maintaining the correct length and width. After printing the parent took the 3D print to the physical therapist for approval. The physical therapist was impressed by how the original design was maintained yet it seemed to be professionally adjusted. Not bad for my first functional design.

I'm thinking about getting into OpenSCAD and perhaps coding a parametric program to assist patients awaiting a customized foot wedge.

Amazons (Designed by Walter Zamkauskas), the game is played on a square grid, usually 10 by 10. Each player starts with four amazons (which move as chess queens, but do not capture) placed in predetermined locations on their side of the board. On a player turn, he moves one amazon and then fires an arrow from the arrival position. Firing an arrow consists in placing a new arrow piece on the board; also the arrow moves like a queen from the position it is fired. The landed arrow doesn't move anymore and creates a permanent block on the board. Arrows can not be passed through by either amazons or other arrows. The first player who can not make a legal move (move and then shoot) loses the game.

title: 60mm Fan Filter Holder for Monoprice Mini Delta
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
The fan on the bottom of the MonoPrice Mini Delta is a great addition since the initial batch as it really helps keep the electronics cool. But, being on the bottom it will be prone to sucking in dust and small debris, and the punched holes in the chassis are really only good for keeping your fingers out.

This 3mm thick filter frame can hold filter media up to 2mm thick to provide improved filtration with minimal airflow reduction and added bulk. The screw pockets are countersunk as deeply as possible to avoid reducing the already minimal penetration.

For best airflow, the printer will need to be elevated a few mm higher than the stock rubber feet provide. This can be done with common rubber feet, or one of many custom designs here on thingiverse.

This filter frame could likely be used on other 60mm fans, but this piece will not separate the filter from the fan, so that function must be provided elsewhere.

For filter media, I used the "Frost King NF305A" AC filter nylon mesh which is cheap and readily available. Simply trim to fit the octagonal pocket.

When assembling to the printer, the power must be disconnected and the bottom plate must be removed. There are metal washers on the inside of the chassis between the fan and chassis which could fall into the electronics. These are apparently needed to keep the fan blades away from the chassis.

title: Christmas Tree with Color Changing LED

description.text:
LED Christmas - I was looking for a simple LED lit Christmas tree that operates similar to tealights, however without switches or the need to solder wires to an LED or CR2032H battery. In short, print it, build it and enjoy it. Oh, and check "LIKE" in Thingiverse :-)

Instructions:
• Print the tree stand using red PLA 20% Fill.
• Print the tree using glow in the dark PLA 12% Fill.
• Purchase a slow color changing LED (3mm 20mA 3V – 3.2V)
• Purchase a CR2032H Battery
• After removing support structures from the tree stand insert the battery into the slot in the back of the stand (Positive facing Right and Negative facing Left). Push the battery all the way into the stand.
• Push the LED into the tree trunk so that the top of the LED slightly protrudes the other end of the trunk. (The longer lead on the LED should go to the positive side of the battery see photos).
• Bend the LED leads over the trunk.
• The tree can only be inserted into the stand one way (look for the key on the tree trunk and stand). Line them up and push the tree trunk into the stand.

Presto you have a color changing LED lit tree ready for Christmas!
Note: there is a small hole in the front of the stand. Use a paperclip to push the battery out and replace when necessary. Remove the tree from the stand to turn it off.

So here is the challenge –
Everyone should print at least one tree and display your tree or forest of trees on every site that allows you to upload photos. Display them everywhere, your house, the internet. Give them to friends that may not have a 3D printer. It would be great to see these little trees across social media, lets light it up.

Please let me know if you like this design and most of all “ENJOY”!

description.text:
Holders for a mirror of about the bed size on the back of the printer to see what it's being printed from the back side.

Each holder have a sliding fit that clamps the 2020 (20 x 20 mm) aluminum profile from the printer's base frame, and another clamp to hold a 4 to 6 mm thick mirror standing up, matching the printer style, leaving enough clearance for the bed to travel backwards and for printed leveling wheels underneath it.

The first STL is the holder that should be printed twice. The second STL is a set of four bands to be optionally printed on the same color from the printer's original rubber ornaments, to glue against the holder to improve the printer style matching.

Notes:

Given the holder's austere smooth surface, it looks fine even if you increase the layer height.I used 0.3 mm height, and 0.2 for the ornamental bands.

If you print the optional bands, glue them against the holder's grooves, they should fit perfectly inside them.

I felt really stupid after buying a 30 x 30 cm mirror, when finding out that being that the printing surface, the bed was actually bigger, leaving me with an extra mirror after buying another one of the bed size: 31 x 31 cm. I don't know you, if you did the same of if you just bought an extra mirror on purpose (as I now can tell people I did!), for the practical purpose of improve your viewing of the piece being printed.

Hence, here it is: a holder to prove that extra mirror worth every penny.

The holder slide fit have clamps that clips in the aluminum frame above and underneath grooves, plus another clip that inserts completely on the side groove. You may leave the rubber ornament in place for an even tighten placement.

Slide the holder from inside the frame and pressing towards the back, ensure the side clip inserts all the way in. You should feel two clipping releasing the pressure, the above/underneath one first and the side clip afterwards. The holder inner surfaces must end up stuck against the metal frame without any free space.

To remove, push it towards the front of the printer.

description.text:
A carriage for the titan aero.. it mounts on the bottom instead of the top. I chose to flip my x axis upside down so that the belts would not get pulled at an angle to the carriage.. this is probably an optional step.

IMPORTANT!! You must reduce the voltage on your pancake stepper or it will get so hot as to warp the carriage. Don't ask me how I know :( I am using the smallest stepper (20mm deep) and reduced to 0.3v. Now it never gets hot to the touch only a bit warm. I think the smallest stepper is the best option since every gram counts and it is very light. However, if you are printing thick layers (0.4mm) you may want a bigger stepper with more torque.

Also, try adding a lock washer between the bearings and the plastic tube spacers.. if you can find one small enough it will let you tighten the bolts as much as you want without causing rubbing between the bearing and the spacer.

Changes to the original (excellent) design include beefing up the parts on the carriage that warped when they got hot and reinforcing the belt holes since with ABS they seemed prone to breaking if you pulled hard on the belt. I can't say enough good things about the original design, the ability to dial in the wheel pressure on the rail really makes all the difference.

Included is a remixed blower mount with tronxy sensor mount added. I'm not really happy with how this turned out, but it is functional. I have some ideas for a new one but they will wait for my new IR sensor to arrive.

description.text: http://geekhaus.com/isci104_fall2017/2017/09/18/mini-drawers/

Updated to larger arm pieces for stability. STL files from before January 12th 2018 are not available anymore.

Safety Disclaimer:
This does not remove solder fumes from your environment. The purpose is to pull them away from your face. Please use adequate ventilation and/or attach a solder fume filter to the back of the fan. Be safe and think about your lungs.

Ideas:
Click the "Remixes" tab to see other great ideas for this project. If you have your own ideas about what to add you can create Side Stations for both stations. The Left and Right sides have two 4mm holes for you to add anything you want of your own design, most common being a custom solder rod holder. Put your name on your adaptation for credit.

Options
80mm fan size and 120mm fan size. The files will have the size in their title if they are for that specific fan size.

On/Off Switch
You will have to figure out the wiring on your own. There is an On/Off switch location at the top of both stations if you would like to wire that into your fan power supply. Easiest would be to have a power supply that fits your fan's voltage/amperage, then wire the power supply negative to the fan's negative, the power supply positive to either the fans positive or the center terminal of your on/off switch and the fan's positive to the side terminal of your on/off switch.

Printing
Use stronger materials such as ABS, PETG, Nylon, or HTPLA for the Ball Joints. This ensures long use and less wear from movement friction.
Ball Joints: There are three options for the Ball/Socket Joints - Standard Fit, Tight Fit, Super Tight Fit. These refer to the distance between the ball and socket. Test out each one to see which is the best for movement vs. stiffness. Stiffer will allow you to hold heavier objects with each arm.
Optional: If the three ball joint options don't work for you then check your horizontal expansion in your slicer to ensure that the arm joints have enough distance between each ball/socket. In Cura it's a setting called Horizontal Expansion - under the Shell settings. A positive number will shrink the shell of your print, a negative will enlarge it. This means that the distance between the ball and socket joints will get larger with a positive setting. If the ball and socket joints are too loose then you can just set a negative number to fix this (start with "-.05"). The Horizontal expansion is in millimeters (mm).

Assembly
1- Find the parts you need from the files listed. 80mm and 120mm fan sized parts are labeled accordingly.
2 - Print the base station parts before the arms. Assemble the fan and wire it up before printing the arms. This will save you a lot of plastic if you printed an error. Let me know if something doesn't work as listed. Try re-downloading the STL file if something doesn't slice properly.
3 - Print the arm Ball Sockets with 70% infill or higher.
4 - Assemble arms from the Alligator Clip end first. Running a heavy single strand wire down the center hole of each piece. Wrap the wire around the Alligator Clip square end to tie it off, as well as around the 3mm bolts at the Base Stations end of each arm. The heavy gauge single stranded wire will keep the arms stiff and upright with even a heavy load. The wire is not absolutely needed if the ball joints are sturdy, but consider adding the wire if the arms have a hard time holding up heavy objects. 14 gauge or larger is best.
5 - Attache as many arms as desired with a maximum of 6 on the 80mm station and 8 on the 120mm station.
6 - The fan should pull the air away and not blow air towards the arms.
7 - screw/bolt the station to your work area if needed. I find that the station design can hold heavy weights without screwing/bolting it down.
8 - The arms are designed to fit standard or larger Alligator Clips. You can use any clamp that you desire on each arm, or attach something else.

Please share any great images with me and I may add them to this page for others to use as reference.

Any ideas for add-ons please let me know! Other clip types, front tray types, etc.
A simply yet versatile soldering station.

Build it, use it, have a way better time soldering!
I am a teacher, if you want an actual lesson plan just ask. This doesn't require one since it is a tool to use in schools, work, and home.
